{{Infobox building |name = Tbilisi Circus |image = Heroes Square, Tbilisi2.jpg |caption = Tbilisi Circus overlooking Heroes' Square in 2008 |building_type = [[Rotunda (architecture)|Rotunda]] |architectural_style = [[Stalinist architecture]] |location = [[Tbilisi]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] |coordinates = {{coord|41|42|51|N|44|47|6|E|display=inline}} |start_date = 1939 |completion_date = 1940 |architect = Nikolay Neprintsev, Vladimer Urushadze, Stepan Satunts }} The '''Tbilisi Circus''' ({{lang-ka|თბილისის ცირკი}}) is the main circus in [[Tbilisi]], the capital of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]. It is housed in a [[Stalinist architecture|Soviet-era Neoclassical]] [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]] building built in 1939 on a hilltop overlooking [[Heroes's Square (Tbilisi)|Heroes' Square]].
== History == === Early history === The history of the Tbilisi circus began in 1888, when the city was part of the [[Russian Empire]]. Its original big top building was destroyed in a fire in 1911 and the circus was moved to a former wine factory, before settling down, in 1939, in its present Neoclassical, [[Joseph Stalin]]-era building designed by Nikolay Neprintsev, Vladimer Urushadze, and Stepan Satunts. The building sit on a hill on the right bank of the [[Kura (Caspian Sea)|Kura river]], near what had been the end of the [[Georgian Military Road]] at the entrance of the city in the imperial era. The hill had also been known for a [[cast iron]] cross, named the Vera Cross after the historical neighborhood, erected in 1847 to commemorate the survival of the emperor [[Nicholas I of Russia|Nicholas I]] in a road accident during his visit to the [[Caucasus]] in 1837. The cross was demolished and the area around it was organized into Heroes' Square under the rule of [[Lavrenti Beria]] in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rukhadze|first1=Ushangi|title=რომელ ცნობილ მოვლენას მიუძღვნეს ვერაზე ჯვრის დადგმა და რომელ ხიდს ამშვენებდნენ თამამშევის ქარვასლიდან წამოღებული გრიფონები|url=http://www.tbiliselebi.ge/?mas_id=268437617&year=2013&rubr_id=27&jurn_id=16|website=Tbiliselebi|accessdate=January 11, 2015|language=Georgian|date=April 15, 2013}}</ref> With its 2,000-seat capacity, the Tbilisi Circus was ranked among the largest circuses in the [[Soviet Union]], alongside those of [[Moscow State Circus|Moscow]], [[Kiev]], and [[Baku State Circus|Baku]].<ref name=eu>{{cite web|last1=Rimple|first1=Paul|last2=Mielnikiewicz|first2=Justyna|title=Georgia: The Tbilisi Circus Comes with Conflict Resolution, Plus Clowns|url=http://www.eurasianet.org/node/66521|website=EurasiaNet.org|accessdate=January 11, 2015|date=February 8, 2013}}</ref>
=== Renovation === A civil unrest and economic collapse in post-Soviet Georgia terminated the circus's heyday in the 1990s. The building fell into disrepair and its territory became notorious for "after-hours" street prostitution.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Meyer|first1=William|last2=Costenbader|first2=Elizabeth C.|last3=Zule|first3=William A.|last4=Otiashvili|first4=David|last5=Kirtadze|first5=Irma|title=‘We are ordinary men’: MSM identity categories in Tbilisi, Georgia|journal=Culture, Health & Sexuality|date=2010|volume=12|issue=8|pages=955-971|doi=10.1080/13691058.2010.516370|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/13691058.2010.516370}}</ref> In 2003, the Georgian tycoon [[Badri Patarkatsishvili]] bought the circus and began an extensive reconstruction, but his involvement in the [[2007 Georgian demonstrations|2007 political crisis]] and death shortly thereafter stalled the renovations. His sister, Mzia Tortladze, was able to reopen the circus only in 2011. Since then, the circus has been playing to sellout crowds, bringing together troupes and performers from various parts of the world.<ref name=eu/>
