{{italic title}} '''''Who's Who of Victorian Cinema''''' is a reference work on film pioneers by Stephen Herbert and Luke McKernan, British scholars of film history.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=British Cinema |quote= ... they'll also be delighted by Stephen Herbert and Luke McKernan's 'Who's Who of Victorian Cinema' - A treasure box of short biographical essays on the medium's ... |publisher=[[The Independent]] |date=March 20, 2005 }}</ref> Originally published by the British Film Institute in 1996 as a reference book, the content has been revised, updated and made available online.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Who's Who of Victorian Cinema. |url=http://intute.ac.uk/artsandhumanities/cgi-bin/fullrecord.pl?handle=humbul11569 |quote=This website, the work of two specialists in film history, is a guide to Victorian film, covering the beginnings of filmmaking, from the 1870s until the death of Queen Victoria in 1901. |publisher=[[Intute]] |date= |accessdate=2007-09-25 }}</ref> The site has biographies of more than 300 pioneers in the film industry, both directors and others who worked behind the cameras. It covers the period from 1895 to 1901, when films rapidly developed as a new way for people to see their worlds.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Victorian film |url=http://www.boingboing.net/2005/01/18/victorian-film.html |quote=Who's Who of Victorian Cinema is a comprehensive collection of obscure info about filmmaking at the end of the 19th century. |publisher=[[BoingBoing]] |date= |accessdate=2007-09-25 }}</ref>
